Dragon Ball Unsupervised Learning

Unsupervised Learning Ideas

Character Clustering

  • Discover hidden archetypes such as Tactical Fighters vs. Energy Blasters or Speed-based vs. Power-based combatants.
    • Fighting style (Ki Blast, Melee Combat, Special Attack)
    • Power Level and Speed Score
    • Transformation Type (Super Saiyan, Fusion, etc.)

Anomaly Detection

  • Find overpowered characters or those with unusual abilities.
    • Identify outliers in Power Score or Transformations.
    • Detect characters with extremely high battle efficiency compared to other
    • Use Isolation Forest or Local Outlier Factor (LOF) to spot anomalies.

Dimensionality Reduction for Visualization

  • Understand how characters group together based on battle abilities.
    • Use PCA (Principal Component Analysis) or t-SNE (t-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding) to visualize relationships between different characters.

Association Rule Mining (Apriori / FP-Growth)

  • Discover common move combinations or transformation patterns.
  • Identify relationships between fighting techniques (Ki Blasts, Special Attacks) and transformation states.

Objective

Selected Project: Character Clustering using Power Level, Speed, and Transformations

Data Preprocessing

  • Transformation column needs to be encoded
  • options
    • One-Hot Encoding (OHE)
      • If the number of unique transformations is low, One-Hot Encoding (OHE) is better since it creates binary columns.
      • Types
        • Ordinal Encoding for Transformation Progression
          • Manually assign numeric values to transformations based on their power progression
        • One-Hot Encoding for Transformation Types
          • equal weight for all transformations
    • Label Encoding
      • If there are many unique transformations, Label Encoding may be better to reduce dimensionality.
    • Frequency Encoding
      • for categorical imbalance
    • Target Encoding
      • correlation with the target variable

from sklearn.preprocessing import (
    StandardScaler, MinMaxScaler, RobustScaler, MaxAbsScaler,
    PowerTransformer, QuantileTransformer, Normalizer
)

#  Load dataset (Modify path if needed)
#file_path = "your_dataset.csv"  # Update with correct file
#data = pd.read_csv(file_path)

#  Select numeric columns only
numeric_features = data.select_dtypes(include=['number']).dropna()

#  Detect Outliers using IQR (Interquartile Range)
def detect_outliers(df):
    outlier_info = {}
    for column in df.columns:
        Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Count outliers
        outlier_count = ((df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)).sum()
        outlier_info[column] = outlier_count

    return outlier_info

outliers = detect_outliers(numeric_features)
outlier_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(outliers, orient='index', columns=['Outlier Count'])

#  Check Skewness (to determine if transformation is needed)
skewness = numeric_features.skew()

#  Scaling Options with All Variants
scalers = {
    "StandardScaler": StandardScaler(),
    "MinMaxScaler": MinMaxScaler(),
    "RobustScaler": RobustScaler(),
    "MaxAbsScaler": MaxAbsScaler(),
    "PowerTransformer (Yeo-Johnson)": PowerTransformer(method="yeo-johnson"),
    "PowerTransformer (Box-Cox)": PowerTransformer(method="box-cox"),
    "QuantileTransformer (Normal)": QuantileTransformer(output_distribution="normal"),
    "QuantileTransformer (Uniform)": QuantileTransformer(output_distribution="uniform"),
    "Normalizer (L1)": Normalizer(norm="l1"),
    "Normalizer (L2)": Normalizer(norm="l2"),
    "Normalizer (Max)": Normalizer(norm="max"),
}

scaler_results = {}

#  Try all scalers & transformations
for scaler_name, scaler in scalers.items():
    try:
        transformed_data = scaler.fit_transform(numeric_features)
        transformed_df = pd.DataFrame(transformed_data, columns=numeric_features.columns, index=numeric_features.index)

        # Calculate variance after scaling (Higher is better)
        cumulative_variance = transformed_df.var().sum()
        scaler_results[scaler_name] = cumulative_variance

    except Exception as e:
        print(f" Error with {scaler_name}: {e}")

#  Convert results to DataFrame and Rank
scaler_rank_df = pd.DataFrame(list(scaler_results.items()), columns=['Scaler', 'Cumulative Variance'])
scaler_rank_df = scaler_rank_df.sort_values(by="Cumulative Variance", ascending=False)

#  Pick the best scaler based on variance ranking
best_scaler_name = scaler_rank_df.iloc[0]["Scaler"]
best_scaler = scalers[best_scaler_name]
scaled_data = best_scaler.fit_transform(numeric_features)

#  Convert Scaled Data to DataFrame
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaled_data, columns=numeric_features.columns, index=numeric_features.index)

#  Save the scaled dataset
scaled_df.to_csv("scaled_dataset.csv", index=False)

#  Explain Selection
explanations = {
    "MinMaxScaler": "Scales data between [0,1]. Used in Unsupervised Learning & Deep Learning but NOT recommended for outliers.",
    "StandardScaler": "Standardizes data to mean=0, variance=1. Recommended for Unsupervised Learning & Deep Learning. Works well with outliers.",
    "RobustScaler": "Uses median and IQR. Best choice for handling outliers in both Unsupervised and Supervised Learning.",
    "MaxAbsScaler": "Scales data between [-1,1]. Used for sparse data, not generally needed for typical datasets.",

    "PowerTransformer (Box-Cox)": "Similar to Yeo-Johnson but works only with strictly positive values. Reduces skewness.",
    "QuantileTransformer (Normal)": "Maps data to a normal distribution. Works well when distribution is unknown.",
    "QuantileTransformer (Uniform)": "Maps data to a uniform distribution. Useful for highly irregular distributions.",
    "Normalizer (L1)": "Normalizes each row by L1 norm. Good for text-based or sparse datasets.",
    "Normalizer (L2)": "Normalizes each row by L2 norm. Often used in clustering tasks.",
    "Normalizer (Max)": "Normalizes each row by its maximum absolute value. Good for text and sparse data."
}

#  Print Summary
print("\n Scaler Rankings:")
print(scaler_rank_df)

print(f"\n Best Scaler Chosen: {best_scaler_name}")
print(f" Reason: {explanations.get(best_scaler_name, 'No explanation available')}")

# Apply PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=14)  # Adjust n_components based on your dataset
data_pca = pca.fit_transform(data_scaled)  # Fit PCA

# Ensure explained_variance_ratio_ exists
explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_

# Define components range
components = np.arange(1, len(explained_variance) + 1)

# Find number of components needed for 70% and 80% variance
n_components_70 = np.argmax(np.cumsum(explained_variance) >= 0.70) + 1
n_components_80 = np.argmax(np.cumsum(explained_variance) >= 0.80) + 1

# Setup for side-by-side plots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 6))

# Plot 1: Explained Variances by Components
axes[0].plot(components, np.cumsum(explained_variance), marker='o', linestyle='--')
axes[0].set_title("Explained Variances by Components")
axes[0].set_xlabel("Number of Components")
axes[0].set_ylabel("Cumulative Explained Variance")
axes[0].grid(True)

# Plot 2: Cumulative Variance with Annotations
axes[1].plot(components, np.cumsum(explained_variance), marker='o', linestyle='--', label="Cumulative Explained Variance")
axes[1].axhline(0.7, color='red', linestyle='--', label="70% Threshold")
axes[1].axhline(0.8, color='green', linestyle='--', label="80% Threshold")

# Annotate important points
axes[1].annotate(f"70% Variance (PC{n_components_70})", xy=(n_components_70, 0.7), xytext=(n_components_70 + 2, 0.65),

In[1494]:
# Finding the least number of components that can explain more than 70%, 80%, 90%, and 95% variance
variance_thresholds = [0.70, 0.80, 0.90, 0.95]  # Variance thresholds to check
threshold_results = {}  # Dictionary to store results

cumulative_sum = 0

for ix, var in enumerate(exp_var):
    cumulative_sum += var  # Accumulate explained variance

    for threshold in variance_thresholds:
        if threshold not in threshold_results and cumulative_sum > threshold:
            threshold_results[threshold] = ix + 1  # Store the number of components

# Display results
for threshold, components in threshold_results.items():
    print(f" Number of PCs that explain at least {int(threshold * 100)}% variance: {components}")

 Number of PCs that explain at least 70% variance: 3
 Number of PCs that explain at least 80% variance: 4
 Number of PCs that explain at least 90% variance: 5
 Number of PCs that explain at least 95% variance: 6
  • 4 components: retain most information while reducing dimensions (80% variance) seem to be a sweet spot
  • 5 - 6 components: better accuracy with slightly more features, (90-95%) are a solid choice
  • 6 or More: minimal value due to diminishing returns

Elbow Method

In[1495]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist

# Define range of clusters
clusters = range(1, 15)
mean_distortions = []

# Apply K-Means for different cluster numbers
for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1, n_init="auto")
    model.fit(data_scaled)  # Fit on PCA-transformed data

    # Calculate distortion (Inertia / Average Distance)
    distortion = np.sum(np.min(cdist(data_scaled, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1)) / data_pca.shape[0]
    mean_distortions.append(distortion)

    print(f"Number of Clusters: {k} \tAverage Distortion: {distortion}")

# Plot Elbow Curve
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(clusters, mean_distortions, "bx-", markersize=8, label="Distortion Score")

# Labels and title
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (k)")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion (Inertia)")
plt.title("Elbow Method for Optimal K Selection", fontsize=14)
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Empty dictionary to store silhouette scores
sc = {}

# Iterate over a range of K values and compute silhouette score
for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1).fit(data_pca)  # Use PCA-transformed data
    labels = kmeans.labels_  # Get cluster labels

    # Compute silhouette score
    sc[k] = silhouette_score(data_pca, labels)

# Plot Silhouette Score for different K values
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(list(sc.keys()), list(sc.values()), 'bx-')

plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters (K)")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.title("Silhouette Score for Optimal K Selection")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Blue Cells:

  • Indicate strong positive contributions of the original features to the principal components.
  • A high positive value means that a feature strongly influences that particular principal component in a positive direction.

Pink Cells:

  • Indicate strong negative contributions. A high negative value means that a feature strongly influences the principal component in the opposite direction.

Interpretation:

  • If a feature has a high positive loading (blue), it plays a significant role in defining that principal component.
  • If a feature has a high negative loading (pink), it also plays a significant role but in the opposite direction.

In[1578]:
# Store models and their names
models_ = [model_kmeans, model_kmedoids, model_agg, model_dbs]
model_names = ["K-Means", "KMedoids", "Agglomerative Clustering", "DBSCAN"]

# List to store scores
scores = []

# Calculate silhouette scores
for model, name in zip(models_, model_names):
    try:
        labels = model.predict(data_scaled)
    except:
        labels = model.labels_

    unique_labels = np.unique(labels)

    if len(unique_labels) > 1:  # Silhouette Score requires at least 2 clusters
        score = silhouette_score(data_scaled, labels)
    else:
        score = -1  # Invalid clustering case

    scores.append((name, score))

# Sort models by silhouette score (Descending)
scores.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

# Print ranked models
print("\n **Ranked Models by Silhouette Score** ")
for rank, (name, score) in enumerate(scores, start=1):
    print(f"{rank}. {name}  Silhouette Score: {score:.4f}")

# Plot silhouette scores
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.bar([x[0] for x in scores], [x[1] for x in scores], color="skyblue")
plt.xlabel("Model")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.title("Silhouette Scores for Different Models")
plt.show()

Silhouette Score Distribution Plot

In[1579]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_samples

def plot_silhouette(model, data, model_name):
    try:
        labels = model.predict(data)
    except:
        labels = model.labels_

    unique_labels = np.unique(labels)

    if len(unique_labels) > 1:  # Only plot if there are at least 2 clusters
        silhouette_vals = silhouette_samples(data, labels)
        y_lower, y_upper = 0, 0
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))

        for i, cluster in enumerate(np.unique(labels)):
            cluster_silhouette_vals = silhouette_vals[labels == cluster]
            cluster_silhouette_vals.sort()
            y_upper += len(cluster_silhouette_vals)

            plt.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper), 0, cluster_silhouette_vals)
            plt.text(-0.05, y_lower + 0.5 * len(cluster_silhouette_vals), str(cluster))
            y_lower = y_upper

        plt.axvline(np.mean(silhouette_vals), linestyle="--", color="red")
        plt.xlabel("Silhouette Score")
        plt.ylabel("Cluster")
        plt.title(f"Silhouette Plot for {model_name}")
        plt.show()

Insights from Clustering Methods

K-Means

  • Pros: Works well when clusters are spherical and evenly sized.
  • Cons: Sensitive to initialization and outliers.

K-Medoids

  • Pros: More robust to outliers than K-Means.
  • Cons: Slower for large datasets.

Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering

  • Pros: Can work well without specifying cluster numbers beforehand.
  • Cons: Computationally expensive for large datasets.

DBSCAN

  • Pros: Can identify arbitrary-shaped clusters and works well with noise.
  • Cons: Requires tuning eps and min_samples.
